    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-09-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-09-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="51"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <head>51. Airgram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Iran</gloss> to the <gloss
                        type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d51fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, POL 23–9 IRAN. Confidential; <gloss target="#t_Noforn1"
                            >Noforn</gloss>. Drafted by Political Officer Victor Wolf, Jr., on
                        September 21. Repeated to Ankara, Baghdad, Cairo, <gloss
                            target="#t_CINCMEAFSA1">CINCMEAFSA</gloss> for <gloss target="#t_POLAD1"
                            >POLAD</gloss>, Jidda, Karachi, and Kuwait.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">A–139</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Tehran</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1964-09-22"
                            >September 22, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Significance of <persName corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName>’s
                        September 9 Speech</item>
                </list>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>REF</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 278<note n="2" xml:id="d51fn2"
                            >Dated September 10. (Ibid.)</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>It now appears that <persName corresp="#p_KAR1">Ayatollah Khomeini</persName>’s
                    speech of September 9 (NIT–6533)<note n="3" xml:id="d51fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    did not include any statement supporting the Mansur Government. The only
                    relatively positive feature of the speech is that, while it criticizes the
                    Iranian regime on numerous counts, it does so somewhat less violently than usual
                    for this dissident clerical leader.</p>
                <p>According to more reliable information [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line of
                        source text not declassified</hi>], the September 9 speech blamed “world
                    colonialism” for the divisions between Shia and Sunni, and “the West” for
                    differences between Iranians and Arabs and other Moslems. <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName> termed the <gloss target="#t_RCD1"
                        >RCD</gloss> a specific instance of such foreign-inspired division among
                    Moslems (although he did not cite the <gloss target="#t_RCD1">RCD</gloss> by
                    name). He inveighed against Israeli and Jewish influence in Iran, complained
                    against lack of freedom of public expression for the religious leaders, and took
                    an oblique swipe at the New Iran Party. [<hi rend="italic">1 line of source text
                        not declassified</hi>]<note n="3" xml:id="d51fn3b">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>On the whole, qualified observers feel that even though <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName> continues to remonstrate against the
                    regime and its policies, there has been a slight toning-down in his position.
                        <gloss target="#t_SAVAK1">SAVAK</gloss> believes the religious situation
                    does not for the moment constitute a serious problem for the security
                    authorities.</p>
                <p>It is possible that a judicious mix of bribery, conciliatory tactics and the
                    ever-present threat of the regime’s mailed fist, has had the effect of lessening
                    somewhat the virulence of <persName corresp="#p_KAR1">Khomeini</persName>’s
                    opposition—although, as his latest speech is now more reliably reported, he is
                    very far indeed from calling for support of the government.</p>
                <closer>For the Charge d’Affaires, a.i. <lb/>
                    <signed>Martin F. Herz</signed>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor of Embassy<lb/>for Political Affairs</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
